Add router ansible test and update network role

Adds a new playbook for testing creating and updating a router.
Also updates network playbook for new 'external' parameter.

The recursive sort utility function in the repository
won't work for python 3 because it can't sort dictionaries
inside lists. Python 2 could but python 3 forbids that.
It does not seem possible to have a simple one size fits all
sorted function to recursively sort lists of dictionaries,
hence just workaround by manually sorting by key or value.

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I2e46bfacf5a8ebdaf0ca50901b7f0262d23833cb
"}]
commit_message:
py34: heat.tests.api.*

The recursive sort utility function in the repository
won't work for python 3 because it can't sort dictionaries
inside lists. Python 2 could but python 3 forbids that.
It does not seem possible to have a simple one size fits all
sorted function to recursively sort lists of dictionaries,
hence just workaround by manually sorting by key or value.

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I2e46bfacf5a8ebdaf0ca50901b7f0262d23833cb

commit_message:
Prevent ilo drivers powering off active nodes during take over

Currently, ilo drivers powers off active nodes
when a conductor takes over the node from another conductor.
This commit stops this, as active nodes shouldn't be powered
off during take over.

Closes-bug: 1490019
Change-Id: I112399f2b746a17d98c7ac4a79f896d1a675039a

commit_message:
Cleanup of Translations

In preparation for the release, do some cleanups for translations.

Removes all po files that are partially translated. The translation
team has decided to exclude files with less than 66 % of translated
content. There is no content lost, all data is in the translation
server, we just remove it from the repository.

This updates also recreates pot (translation source files) to
reflect the state of the repository in case there was no recent
import for them.

This change needs to be done manually since the automatic import does
not handle some of these cases.

Change-Id: I6b436ddc04f2f866dcb795d4d7c1c44d816dcadf

commit_message:
fix literal rendering in dictionary options docs

Fix the syntax error in the python example for dictionary options so
pygments will render it properly.

Use a code-block directive to tell pygments that the inline INI file is
an INI file, since it does not figure that out automatically.

Closes-Bug: #1413389
Change-Id: I16441739e6cbfe8ad497aa0860fbc85a4a2d8123

commit_message:
docs - Set pbr 'warnerrors' option for doc build

By setting this pbr option in setup.cfg, the doc build will fail in case
of any warnings or errors occur during the build process.

Change-Id: Icfca280be8abadce50cbf5ed7fa82ba67a3556ae

commit_message:
Fix for keystone LDAP pkg missing

This change adds the python-ldap package to keystone by default and
improves the conditional by which the ldap domain specific config
drivers are loaded.

Change-Id: Idf85bb109654cbb46755928504d6a19c090a7514
Closes-bug: 1497669
(cherry picked from commit f32def0216b042aa31f4736e9e863cf2332dfbe7)

commit_message:
Port image_utils to Python 3

Port cinder.image_utils.check_qemu_img_version() to Python 3.

Add the following tests to Python 3.4 in tox.ini:

* cinder.tests.unit.test_image_utils
* cinder.tests.unit.test_migrations
* cinder.tests.unit.test_misc
* cinder.tests.unit.test_service

Partially implements: blueprint cinder-python3
Change-Id: I69feda94c90206adc8771fbd5ddc6aae5bb6b64b

commit_message:
docs - Set pbr warnerrors option for doc build

By setting this pbr option in setup.cfg, the doc build will fail in case
of any warnings or errors occur during the build process.

Change-Id: I1f70ea5c6b26b30d5c5583934333053ef065fbf6

commit_message:
Missing configuration opts from cinder.sample.conf

The logic for writing opts registered with register_opt() to the
auto-generated opts.py file was flawed in that the directories where
there were opts being registered with this method would be imported,
but the actual opt would be missed when looking through the file for
the name of the opt being registered. Now the singular opts are being
caught and written to opts.py for the oslo-config-generator to process.

The 'backend' section was added to generate_cinder_opts.py
due to some of the missing opts being a part of that section.

Also the way some of the opts that were being registered with groups
were incorrect and so this addresses those in both how they were
processed in generate_cinder_opts.py and the files in which they are being
registered.

There is also one change to the name of an opt in cinder/volume/api.py.
Instances such as this one will be caught by the in-progress hacking
check patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/223375/

Change-Id: I8d333d7529d40f3a3b3651ca3a52c0048d96b99a
Closes-Bug: #1498122

commit_message:
Activate pep8 check that _ is imported

Remove the specification in tox.ini that _ is a builtin so that
it will no longer assume that _ does not need to be imported.
This helps ensure that the _ from i18n is used.

Activating this check did not flag any violations.

Change-Id: Iac73937b60a6f8e7520123fbf59e748d296d4c7d

commit_message:
Remove Tuskar from the CLI usage

The command line workflows with Tuskar have proven to be more limited than
using Heat directly. This change removes Tuskar from the CLI documentation and
updates all the examples.

Essentially this means removing all uses of --plan in the deploy command and
all other 'openstack management ...' commands.

Tuskar is still referenced in a number of places and can't be fully removed
until there is an alternative for the Tuskar UI.

Change-Id: I2d4aa114156c5bafb003e6a67862ed6d1449fd98

commit_message:
docs - Set pbr 'warnerrors' option for doc build

By setting this pbr option in setup.cfg, the doc build will fail in case
of any warnings or errors occur during the build process.

Change-Id: I508d93249c5243b0068fe71ccb1726441a64d145

commit_message:
Correct the comment of __call__ method

The comment of return value is incorrect
in class ConfigOpt's _call_ method.
Now the comment of return value is described as below:
"returns: the list of arguments left over after parsing options"
but,actually, the method should not have return value.
So I delete the comment of return value.

Change-Id: I9bf5a412cf0a6f9ad70ea373716279154975b85d
Closes-Bug:1498378

commit_message:
Ensure Alembic version modules bootstrap new db

The current Alembic version modules (including the initial juno one)
were not able to bring a database up from a new/fresh state (at least
for Postgresql). This CR adjusts the version files to support this,
including replacing some dialect-busting op.execute(...) calls with
generic op calls.

Change-Id: Idf1fffb1a55203a5db47ea28bab2502db69a977e
Closes-bug: #1499396

The recursive sort utility function in the repository
won't work for python 3 because it can't sort dictionaries
inside lists. Python 2 could but python 3 forbids that.
It does not seem possible to have a simple one size fits all

commit_message:
py34: heat.tests.api.cfn

The recursive sort utility function in the repository
won't work for python 3 because it can't sort dictionaries
inside lists. Python 2 could but python 3 forbids that.
It does not seem possible to have a simple one size fits all
sorted function to recursively sort lists of dictionaries,
hence just workaround by manually sorting by key or value.

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I3b8073208baa9927aa8054cea600f627608caa4f

commit_message:
Add reference guide documenting Certificate Authorities API

Document the APIs and their parameters, attributes, and status codes.

Also change the returned status code from 405 to 409 when a user
attempts to remove-from-project a preferred CA.

Change-Id: I6a0bffa84c8dfb303580b5b050bda8aedb8277ad
Partially-implements: blueprint add-cas

commit_message:
py34: test_loguserdata/test_ec2_token

* convert ec2token object into dictionary before serialising
* IOError is a subclass of OSError in python3, so use the return
  code of OSError in test case assertion only for python3

partial blueprint heat-python34-support

Change-Id: I890a3fb78ac4903fd523e513130d70f08c7f4718

commit_message:
Add flag to prevent VLAN cleanup

This change set provides operators with a flag to limit the automated
clean up of the VLANs from the neutron agent.  If set to True, the
system will not periodically clean up VLANs that are not in use.

Change-Id: Ica25220bf5f3dbe4541f012506c542732f2dca8e
Closes-Bug: 1497439

commit_message:
Change small graphs per job to sparklines

The small graphs for failures and runtime for each job of a project
looks better if we use sparkline based graphs, a sample is
provided by highcharts http://www.highcharts.com/demo/sparkline and
I based this work on that.

Change-Id: I52d3445d5fc7984e1fe6235de11280da812ba056
Co-Author: Dhiana Deva <ddeva@thoughtworks.com>

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-16 21:07:11.000000000', 'message': 'Update cached LXC image in place

The LXC container creation playbook is one of the longest-running playbooks
in the repository.  It generally takes 15-17 minutes to run during the gate
jobs.  Much of this time is spent updating each container with the latest
packages.

This patch causes the LXC cached image to be updated one time before that
image is used for all of the containers.  It reduces the amount of times the
updates actually run and this shortens the time it takes to complete the
playbook.

So far, this brought the playbook timing from 15-17 minutes down to about
4-5 minutes.

The updates to the cached image will only occur if a new cache image has
just been downloaded.

Partial-bug: 1489169

commit_message:
Update cached LXC image in place

The LXC container creation playbook is one of the longest-running playbooks
in the repository.  It generally takes 15-17 minutes to run during the gate
jobs.  Much of this time is spent updating each container with the latest
packages.

This patch causes the LXC cached image to be updated one time before that
image is used for all of the containers.  It reduces the amount of times the
updates actually run and this shortens the time it takes to complete the
playbook.

The updates to the cached image will only occur if a new cache image has
just been downloaded.

Partial-bug: 1489169

Change-Id: Iba64f9a3aeb999907088f2a99e8904700074550b

commit_message:
Revert "Revert "Add translation-jobs for python-keystoneclient""

I'm sorry about this. We discussed some more in the i18n team
and since keystone library is used in openstackclient, it
might be worth translating this. So, let's enable the infrastructure.

This reverts commit 6e90a9a5e36603c094ce0bf41cb087bc5b3236b0.

Change-Id: I5bafa7e384c5921932609a14ae40f57923e011d8

commit_message:
zuul/layout/puppet: add more integration jobs

Puppet OpenStack Integration job is testing Heat (WIP), Sahara, Cinder,
and Ceilometer.

This patch adds the jobs to the projects, still non-voting for now.

supported in vCenter 5.5 and above.

Rename swift-readme.rst to swift-guide.rst

All services should have a guide that follows the same style as
cinder-guide.rst or swift-guide.rst and all should be named
service-guie.rst.

subject: Fix the repository to openstack

We dont require bug reports for doc changes'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-13 05:11:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

Thanks for the work!  Note Mandre in a different review suggested using the proper master github repo which is:

git://git.openstack.org/openstack/kolla

Would you mind adjusting your patch with said address?'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-09-13 17:03:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Also note for future work, bugs are not required for docs improvements (only code), to lower the pain threshold to improving the documentation :)

Regards
-steve'}, {'account_id': 10428, 'date': '2015-09-13 20:11:01.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I'm agree with Steve on this one :)"}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-09-14 01:43:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I disagree with using the git:// url. Lots of firewalls block that. That is the reason github itself defaults to the https:// url for clones. Lets stick with the default that github itself uses.'}, {'account_id': 1390, 'date': '2015-09-14 09:31:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 13039, 'date': '2015-09-14 12:08:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

SamYaple, git.openstack.org also provides firewall friendly URL: https://git.openstack.org/openstack/kolla

Doc may also be updated to point to docs.openstack.org.

See my comments on https://review.openstack.org/#/c/213413/'}, {'account_id': 14119, 'date': '2015-09-16 11:30:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

ah sure mandre. I dont care about _where_ its cloned from as much as how its cloned. https would be my preference for firewall reasons.

But for the record openstack.org is notoriously slow and down far more often than github in my experience. That said I don't really have an opinion on where the docs point to, just the clone protocol."}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-09-18 18:00:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sam,

I prefer github as well, and I think a majority of the OpenStack community uses the github mirrors because they are highly reliable and fast and provide nice line number linking and good introspection.

However, our docs should point to the master repositories in all cases not mirrors (unless a mirror is the only way something operates, like in the case of centos repositories).  I am good with https as a protocol type rather then git.

venkatamahesh,

Would you mind updating the patch to use https and the openstack master location for the repository?'}, {'account_id': 3098, 'date': '2015-09-25 17:17:35.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 2834, 'date': '2015-09-25 17:18:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-25 17:47:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

- gate-kolla-build-images-centos-source http://logs.openstack.org/97/222897/2/check/gate-kolla-build-images-centos-source/14148e1/ : FAILURE in 22m 37s (non-voting)
- gate-kolla-build-images-ubuntu-source http://logs.openstack.org/97/222897/2/check/gate-kolla-build-images-ubuntu-source/93a6199/ : FAILURE in 28m 43s (non-voting)'}, {'account_id': 16237, 'date': '2015-09-25 18:06:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Steven Dake,
By cross checking with other projects, major projects are using "github" rather than "openstack" for cloning source.
But giving preference for master "OpenStack" is a good idea.
I think all projects should maintain a unique one for cloning either using with "github" or "openstack".

openstack

determined that using openstack repos is best.)

commit_message:
Update the AIO build convenience script

This updates the AIO build convenience script, removing the use of the
gate-check-commit script - as that is specifically for gating - and
instead using the same process that is recommended to a developer in
the development-stack document.

Change-Id: I81c58556f36d60f998b071a705a11b445be6a876
(cherry picked from commit 88b85827b98c11126a2debae98b615d45a3e0045)

commit_message:
Fix parititions schema for IBP

If the upgrade target environment was provisioned by other method than
image-based provisioning ('image'), then we need to repair partitions schema.
Otherwise, node is expected to have proper partitions in metadata.

Change-Id: I5c5f1f74c6e5cc0ca0d671fb23e7149d12ba4589

Current swift datasource driver doesn't provide auth options while

commit_message:
Handle an asset service schema version

Add a version flag to allow fields to be added to assets
that are required for proper fuctioning of that asset type that
this version of the pluging will flag as unsupported rather then
partially but brokenly support.

Change-Id: Id85d7b0a13dbc8e290a01835e531f5998d6e2324

commit_message:
Missing tests for rule_model

This commit adds tests for rule_model in api/test_rule_model,
which were missing before and also moves relavant rule_model
tests from test_congress to api/test_rule_model.

Related-Bug:#1398640

commit_message:
Change to use tempest plugin framework

Tempest plugin framework provides more flexibility for projects.
With this plugin, it's not requiring the tests live in the tempest
tree.

Change-Id: I8681140d02926b4b3e6af84b8f03b9385e62cc72

It would be better to drop the symbolic link antlr3 and use a real dependency, but it requires to add first antlr_python_runtime (3.1.3) to global requirements.

commit_message:
Remove one local copy of the Python antlr3 module

* Remove the directory thirdparty/antlr3/
* Modify the antlr3 symbolic link to point to
  thirdparty/antlr3-antlr-3.5/runtime/Python/antlr3/

Change-Id: I8104b7352e96d8e282da4e5bd8ff4fb4817aaa32

commit_message:
Fix TypeError on restarting congress service

After creation of 'database' and 'materialized' kind policies,
restarting API service throws TypeError. This commit fixes the same.

Change-Id: I16a618910eb1e4713534ed2d4a97c4675b91b8f3
Closes-Bug:#1498771

commit_message:
Fix subprocess exception name

https://review.openstack.org/227299 added code using
subprocess.CheckedProcessException, which does not exist. From
the Python documentation, it should be
subprocess.CalledProcessError [1]

[1] - https://docs.python.org/2/library/subprocess.html#subprocess.CalledProcessError

Change-Id: I0e03f048a33b1b919e38d22038650a633b8ac5fd

commit_message:
Fix state computation incorrect

The Resource of oslo-incubator is used as the
super class of client object in novaclient and
cinderclient, but the implemented of __eq__ method
don't match the semantics of object equal. Check
equal between two objects by using obj1 == obj2,
that will always be True if the objects have the
same id, even if they have the different other
attribute value. The issue had been traced by
oslo-incubator bug/1499369, fix it in Congress side
as temporary workaround in order to avoid the issue
exist in stable/liberty branch.

Change-Id: I4304c32432dc1f813377c60704f817b4f3020da2
Closes-Bug: #1499065
(cherry picked from commit 897bcfca781835e73736d9e232a647a817aa8759)

commit_message:
Fix swift auth problem

Current swift datasource driver doesn't provide auth options while
creating a swift client due to historical reason.

Change-Id: I1493143d558e1aef10feb504363d6efb758c16cf
Closes-Bug: #1499018

commit_message:
Python 3 incompatible expression fix

In Python 3 dict.keys() return iterable view which
does not support indexing. This patch fixes the issue by using
appropriate iterator functions.

Implements: bp cinder-python3
Change-Id: Ib31531e5890fb050ce3c03ea0a078afd2122abe4

commit_message:
Reuse existing template

Extend the "-x" option on the CLI and API for the stack update
to reuse the existing raw template saved in the database for a stack.
This allows the users to optionally omit the template when
specifying the "-x" option.  The template can be specified or
omitted independently of other options.
Usage:
Use the new template:
  heat stack-update mystack -x -f mynewtemplate.yaml
Reuse the existing template:
  heat stack-update mystack -x

Partial-Bug: 1224828
Change-Id: I7df4eb107881b673bf5733bbc2d4cc3d9a319d21

commit_message:
Remove task validation from api.Task.start

The goals of this patch:
* to separate log output of task validation and task start printout.
* don't create task db record and set task's status during
  'rally task validate'

commit_message:
Remove NetApp drivers from Cinder

The following commit: If51c13ade0497c8e89b044bebb393b52da62029a
introduced a dependency on a proprietary licensed library into the
Cinder code base.  There are differing opinions on the legal
ramifications here (if any), however what is clear is that in
principle we have always focused on keeping ALL of OpenStack open,
and not having an "open core" with proprietary components that
were in tree.

Additionally, it seems that it's been discovered that this proprietary
library includes work from the OpenStack code that was not submitted
by NetApp or it's reprsentatives and said work was not sighted nor
any credit given to the original source.

My first proposal was to revert the change that introduced the new
library, however that particular strategy has some issues due to the
large number of changes that have been made to the NetApp drivers since
this change landed.  There is an extensive list of merge conflicts
that frankly I'm not familiar enough with to try and work through.

This patch proposes the removal of the NetApp drivers.  The suggestion
is that someone interested in fixing this can submit a modified revert
of this removal patch which puts the code back in place but removes
the dependency on the proprietary library.

Change-Id: I552940ee401f241f2fc4ab238c964fb7cc95d0a0
Partial-Bug: #1499334
(cherry picked from commit f4a23c64e23ccb13044c4e77f072d15e3c40b26c)

commit_message:
No auth when token and endpoint are passed

The latest change to the auth_required logic introduced a bug were even
when the token and endpoint were passed, authentication was being
required.

This patch fixes that issue and makes sure that authentication is not
required when these 2 arguements are present.

Closes-bug: #1499540

Change-Id: I4c9c15ba526378970da5461511ed922d42c5a9f9

commit_message:
Add SSL/TLS listener to RabbitMQ

This patch adds a SSL/TLS listener to RabbitMQ without disrupting the existing
plaintext TCP listener.  Various services that use RabbitMQ will have the
option to encrypt messaging traffic with this change.  Documentation is
included for this change.

By default, it will create a self-signed certificate for the user, but users
have the option to specify their own existing certificates as well.

This makes it easier to bring RabbitMQ (and the services which talk to it)
into compliance with PCI DSS 3.1's Requirement 2.2.3.

In addition, this change is recommended within the OpenStack Security Guide.

Closes-bug: 1496001

Change-Id: I0d29cbb6e963b24f77a8375eba8a8c6a558aaf81

docs - Set pbr 'warnerrors' option for doc build

By setting this pbr option in setup.cfg, the doc build will fail in case
of any warnings or errors occur during the build process.

Change-Id: I14a08843c34529e9d4f4f3b07ad926e3f9b290d6

commit_message:
Add thread policy note to virt-driver-cpu-pinning

CPU thread policy manipulation was ultimately not implemented as part of
the virt-driver-cpu-pinning work done in Kilo and now exists (or at
least did for Liberty, pending re-proposal for Mitaka) as a separate
proposal.

This patch updates the original specification to note this and add a
link to the newer blueprint in the hope of removing confusion.

Change-Id: If014840ac5a79dfaeffc56dd56d9627bc0208324

commit_message:
Add net.netfilter.nf_conntrack_max to Swift Storage

With the default sysctl value, the nf_contract table fills and starts
dropping packets on Swift storage nodes after a certain period of time.

This is not a problem in Kilo as the value is set to 256k in all hosts
by default. Adding this specifically to the storage setup to avoid
adding the more complex solution used for nova/neutron that uses var
files in playbooks.

Change-Id: Ic9162eeb50523b32f477075b565f55bbf868d1d6
Closes-Bug: #1451217
Closes-Bug: #1479127

commit_message:
Add all tenants search opt to del instnce by name

Nova delete command deletes an instance by name
or ID. Nova delete command is able to delete an
instance within the same the tenant by name or
ID. When admin credentials are sourced and try
to delete a non admin tenant instances, nova
delete command is able to delete an instance by
ID only, it is not able to delete an instance by
name.

Nova delete command deletes an instances by id
using following api call
/v2/{tenant_id}/servers/{server_id}
But to delete an instance by name, nova delete
command first find the resources by name using
following api call
/servers?name={server_name}
This api call is not able to retrive the list
of other tenant instances.
Adding all tenants parameter to this api call
will retrive the list of other tenant
instances. The following will be new api
call
/servers?all_tenants=1&name={server_name}

Closes-Bug: #1247030

Change-Id: I03e578d58214c835d9a411752bd618d77ced37ff

When we took out watchdog we did not take out the parameter
that was setting it to true when setting up statsd resulting
in it not starting up

commit_message:
Fix HNAS manage CLI examples

The CLI examples of the manage functionality in HNAS documentation do not
work due to a missing parameter.
This patch fixes the referenced commands and perform some other minor
adjustments.

Change-Id: I7a3fb31f2526eb48ef2f896d62605b85f09a659c
Closes-bug: #1498154

But it looks like there may be something wrong with your environment because I have almost the same HW/SW and I have never seen such problems with glance.'}, {'account_id': 11391, 'date': '2015-09-22 13:26:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

Looks good and I agree with the whole idea! One small nit in docstring and I'll +2 it."}, {'account_id': 7703, 'date': '2015-09-22 18:16:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Kairat, thanks you so much for your review comments. I have a Mac and sometime ago when I tried running whole of glance test suite, some of them failed on Mac but realized it all passes on linux (to confirm if this still happens). Hence, this time around, I spun up a VM using Virtualbox with 8GB RAM & 2 vcpus with Ubuntu 12.04 LTS as the OS. 

In the machine my first git clone was only glance and nothing else installed. Despite that I faced this failure consistently, after spending quite amount of time digging into the issue, I realized that only bumping up the timeout could solve this problem. 

Honestly, I was not satisfied with bumping up the timeout value and submitting a patch for the same. But then I felt that this could be a genuine issue and there could be people with probably some similar slow machines (like mine) who could get their tests passing consistently even though the test runs will be slower on their machines. 
For rest of the community with better machines, there would be no harm due to this change as the tests waiting for servers start will resume even within the original timeout set (10 secs) without any side effect.

Hence as per @Mike's CR, I am going to fix the doc string and push an updated patch for review.
@Mike, thanks for reviewing the patch.

I am also trying to figure out if my system has got some issues. Soon I will get it fixed if any issue found."}, {'account_id': 7703, 'date': '2015-09-22 18:23:13.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 5314, 'date': '2015-09-22 18:35:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-22 19:25:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

commit_message:
Fix server start ping timeout for functional tests

When we run the functional tests using 'tox -epy27',
the functional tests keeps failing due to ping timeout
that happens after server starts (api, registry etc.,)
in order to run the functional tests. Could make the tests
pass only after increasing the ping timeout.

This minor patch fixes ping timeout issue by increasing the timeout
value from 10 to 30 seconds for ensuring consistent success of
functional tests. Found any value lesser than 30 secs still continue
to fail the tests.

Closes-bug: #1497508
Change-Id: If1c5fc69ae34c976de2a0c5e9e70810b5b994491

[{'created': '2015-09-25 00:17:13.000000000', 'message': "Release resources allocated to the Instance when it gets deleted

Currently when application get deleted its servers are also get deleted,
but all underlying allocated OpenStack resources remain so.

This commit makes the following to happen upon deletion:
* Exclude OS::Nova::Server resource from the stack
* Exclude all FloatingIP and related resources allocated for the server
* Exclude Neutron ports allocated to the server
* Exclude all Heat Software Configs (in case of HeatSWConfigInstance)
   created by the app
* Exclude all HOT template outputs related to deleted resources

Also:
* Instance class gets releaseResources method that can be used by apps to explicitly
  destroy the server. It can be recreated later again using deploy method
* The order in which .destroy() methods get called was changed so that the owner's
   destructor be called before that of the owned object. For example application
   destructor will be executed prior to its Instance destructor. This allows application
   to delete all references to the server that is going to be destroyed. Thus Heat template
   remains consistent.

Change-Id: I42d9adf827688232d89b7f01ee1176e3151c65a1
Closes-Bug: #1499563
"}]
commit_message:
Release resources allocated to the Instance when it gets deleted

Currently when application get deleted its servers are also get deleted,
but all underlying allocated OpenStack resources remain so.

This commit makes the following to happen upon deletion:
* Exclude OS::Nova::Server resource from the stack
* Exclude all FloatingIP and related resources allocated for the server
* Exclude Neutron ports allocated to the server
* Exclude all Heat Software Configs (in case of HeatSWConfigInstance)
   created by the app
* Exclude all HOT template outputs related to deleted resources

Also:
* Instance class gets releaseResources method that can be used by apps to explicitly
  destroy the server. It can be recreated later again using deploy method
* The order in which .destroy() methods get called was changed so that the owner's
   destructor be called before that of the owned object. For example application
   destructor will be executed prior to its Instance destructor. This allows application
   to delete all references to the server that is going to be destroyed. Thus Heat template
   remains consistent.

Change-Id: I42d9adf827688232d89b7f01ee1176e3151c65a1
Closes-Bug: #1499563

commit_message:
Security utilities for fuzz tests

This file contains helper methods used for security fuzz tests. It
generates datasets that can be used in parameterized test cases, and
verifies responses to API requests to ensure that they do not contain
indicators of vulnerability.

Change-Id: I3f8e3f65061f18f3242d34a7e529b2f652bd573e

commit_message:
Introduce Sahara extended logging class

There is a range of extended logging options in Openstack services that use
openstack.common.logger (Ceilometer, Cinder, Heat, Keystone, Nova).
Adding ceilometer::logging to support them like it done for puppet-heat,
puppet-ceilometer, puppet-cinder, etc.

Change-Id: I389fabeca8ae3013e44ad3e1a7665118814fc69c

commit_message:
Fixed pattern matching

Directory plugin was trying to match the entire file path instead
of only matching the file name (as provided in the config)

Change-Id: I54220d48e7e8e27cc1a53dd2ab2e5640b50dbe8e

commit_message:
Remove default value when attaching a policy

The default value will overwrite the attributes of policy,
when options(level, cooldown) are not configured, use the
policy's default values.

Change-Id: I4137bb81c82dcca3b96e6c4ec441dc3a27951eaf

commit_message:
Convert to int can cause different error messages

Starting from python3.4.3 casting list to int, i.e. int([]) returns
exception with another messge. Try to fix.

Co-Authored-By: Pavlo Shchelokovskyy <pshchelokovskyy@mirantis.com>
Closes-Bug: #1499470

(1 comment)

Egor : The logic used here is :-
1. First check whether the Bay exist
2. If #1 is successful then only proceed ahead to get the pods by bay uuid.

This query is not used as frequently as query-by-name or query-by-id; so performance wise we will only git a slight hit when this API is invoked. But as the frequency is less I don't see it as a major concerns. 

But again we want to be precautions and hence the check "self.get_bay_by_uuid". Precaution is better than cure :)

HTH'}, {'account_id': 8143, 'date': '2015-08-28 19:38:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

@jay : sure; will submit a patch to fix all the 3 resources rc, service, pod.'}, {'account_id': 9591, 'date': '2015-08-30 15:11:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Good to catch a potential performance bottleneck.  Current code in get_services_by_bay_uuid and get_rcs_by_bay_uuid already has this check for bay existence in the db, but it's not necessarily good to repeat the same check for get_pods_by_bay_uuid. Since the second query would fail anyway, a trivial fix would be to change the exception to be less specific and say that the bay or the pods/rcs/services do not exist.  This should give enough info for the user to troubleshoot and limit the db query to just one.  The alternative is to add more logic somehow to distinguish the cases."}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-08-31 18:50:33.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-08-31 18:54:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Proposed to remove the dead code. Discussed it with HongBin and Kennan on IRC. 

Marking it as WIP to make sure we all are on same page and to see if anyone has any concerns regarding the same."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:41:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified+1

I think we should not remove the code. It should be used in PodsController. I found that the detail function in PodsController has a pod_uuid parameter which is documented to get only pods for that pod. It is strange. I think the pod_uuid should be replaced by bay_uuid. It is common to show all the pods in a bay. You can fix this bug instead of removing the code.'}, {'account_id': 10263, 'date': '2015-09-01 18:28:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Discussed with Hua on IRC and his only opposition for this patch is that we might need an API of the sort in future.

magnum pod-list --bay-uuid xxxxxxx

and hence we should not remove the code.

This API is sometime in future and doesn't exist today we don;t even know if we plan to have such an API as there is no blueprint/spec for the same.

We have 2 options here  :-

1. Do not remove the dead code and make use of it when we implement cli of the sort "magnum pod-list --bay-uuid xxxxxxx". In that case make the exception more intuitive like PodNotFoundNoBayExist vs what we have now BayNotFound [2].

OR

2. Remove the dead code now and whenever in future we add this new CLI add the code to filter out the pod list by bay_uuid. Open a bug to track it and fix it. In that case the current patch holds true.

commit_message:
Remove unused DB API and Pod object API

This patch removes unused DB API 'get_pods_by_bay_uuid',
Pod object layer API 'list_by_bay_uuid' and the
associated unit tests. There are no consumers of this
code as this code is not invoked by anyone. Cleaning
this up will help to remove some dead code.

Change-Id: If0bed177d190040720e50bf15dfefb5de5a7b999
Closes-Bug: #1489572

functionality of the plugin.

commit_message:
Move the code for local cert to the right place

devstack/lib/magnum#L184-188 was temporary work until barbican is
available, but they are still needed only for local cert manager when
barbican is not enabled.
Therefore move these lines into a location that runs only if it use
local cert manager.

By the way, remove the comments that no one need anymore and fixed
some indentations a little.

Change-Id: I74b4b82b26f6a80fd03a8055b9bd8c02715962a5

commit_message:
Specify that EPEL needs to be enabled on CentOS

As of now it is not mentionned that EPEL should be enabled for CentOS
hosts. This leads to the following error while running
`instack-virt-setup`:

EPEL repository is required to install python-pip for CentOS

Sources :

* https://github.com/openstack/instack-undercloud/blob/master/scripts/instack-virt-setup#L44
* https://github.com/openstack/tripleo-incubator/blob/master/scripts/install-dependencies#L62-L66

Change-Id: I17fdbd4880dcdefeadf7a3512f468309f1a71e6c

commit_message:
docs - Set pbr 'warnerrors' option for doc build

By setting this pbr option in setup.cfg, the doc build will fail in case
of any warnings or errors occur during the build process.

Change-Id: I861b6de50aaa5a30db1b18474b2554743a9968c7

commit_message:
Add ebtables to neutron agent configuration

Neutron now uses ebtables as an extra security layer for ARP
spoof filtering. This patch adds the ebtables package and
rootwrap to the neutron role to ensure that the agent is able
to use this subsystem. Without it the networking from the
instances to the L3 router will fail.

Co-Authored-By: Evan Callicoat <diopter@gmail.com>
Closes-Bug: #1482756
Change-Id: Ibc960564a3acfbb10cfbc3cfe0ad60d3366d2443
(cherry picked from commit a1eebe6afd0f042eaa161d41d9bab4ac3c2bfe77)

-1 just because I have a question and want to be noticed ;-)

Is there any reason a user would reference these files in a custom resource registry?  I'm thinking not, unless they did a complete copy-paste job on the base resource registry file, but I think it's an important point to consider so I want to make sure.  If users would have references to these files then I'd rather live with the redundancy than break them without a deprecation path.

In general, this gets back to my previous griping about our wishy-washy public "api"s.  It seems to me that these are essentially a private interface, but we don't have an accepted way of making that explicit for Heat templates. :-/'}, {'account_id': 360, 'date': '2015-08-06 14:32:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-06 14:33:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

Ben: Good question. And in general I think one of the selling points of nested stacks is that they could be useful as a stand alone Heat stack.

For TripleO however that ship sailed long ago because we have this "AllNodesData" stuff going on. What this means is that the compute role for example isn't really useful as a standalone because it isn't a complete piece of a role. It just represents part of the picture. To get the whole role you have to have the base configuration, all nodes configuration, and post-deployment stacks all in place to run things. And while someone could certainly do that in a separate stack I don't think it very likely.

I view them as internal interfaces and see this as a simple internal cleanup that shouldn't really effect the end user much.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-06 17:13:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified-1

commit_message:
Rename -puppet.yaml templates.

Updates the /puppet directory templates so that we drop the
'-puppet' from the filenames. This is redundant because
we already have puppet in the directory name and fixes
inconsistencies where we aren't using -puppet in
all the files within the puppet directory.

Depends-On: I71cb07b2f5305aaf9c43ab175cca976e844b8175

Change-Id: I70d6e048a566666f5d6e5c2407f8a6b4fd9f6f87

commit_message:
Change defaults value for Sahara Keystone credentials

Rename defaults value for keystone user and keystone tenant name
to be consistent with defaults in keystone::auth class and other
openstack puppet modules.

Change-Id: I4a8e76f9e9d3e45987029c9b2ce3b9f5eb964921

commit_message:
FWaaS delete actions refactoring

FWaaS delete actions are implemented in an unusual way and have
a lot of unnecessary code. This change makes some clean up.

Closes-Bug: #1492281

Change-Id: Ie58f4be5a2fa1142897669e5f85bc8c983795baa

commit_message:
Make generation of ironic.conf.sample deterministic

This commit makes the generation of ironic.conf.sample
more deterministic by sorting the options belonging
to the same group based on module in which they are
defined before printing them.

It also fixes a small bug which caused options to
appears in different group in sample file generated
when they are the same (like [cisco_ucs]max_retry and
[cimc]max_retry which are of same type, have same default
value and same description).

Change-Id: Ifd336e2ec680a286e8789c2046bda2cb9ddbaf08
Closes-Bug: 1498113

commit_message:
Cleanup of Translations

In preparation for the release, do some cleanups for translations.

Removes all po files that are partially translated. The translation
team has decided to exclude files with less than 66 % of translated
content. There is no content lost, all data is in the translation
server, we just remove it from the repository.

This updates also recreates pot (translation source files) to
reflect the state of the repository in case there was no recent
import for them.

This change needs to be done manually since the automatic import does
not handle some of these cases.

Change-Id: I1d54433aa8cac18969e2156f58e9d166a167675f

commit_message:
Rely on cluster's status instead node status

Currently, we have an issue related to nailgun task model.
Nailgun switches node to ready status before all node's tasks
will be finished. Issue is absent if we rely on cluster's
status.

Change-Id: I73294b799917b33f7f408ba6a267ab313f478f83

commit_message:
scenario001: enable telemetry service

* Install & configure Ceilometer services
* Configure Nova to send events to RabbitMQ
* Configure Glance to send events to RabbitMQ
* Enable telemetry tests in Tempest

Depends-On: I2b8d55613f0a962662d67b9fd82db17b758af80f
Change-Id: I8690007e9a3be3c0188777f859b517375d95ec1d

commit_message:
Document --plugin-paths/RALLY_PLUGIN_PATHS

These options were added in 71d01a but were never added to the
docs. This removes the five duplicate places that plugin placement was
discussed, and replaces them with a single place that documents the
"new" options.

commit_message:
Make format of multiple PTLs consistent

Have two usages in file using either 'and' or '&' to join the multiple
PTLs. Switch to using '&'.

Change-Id: Idba08d99c5789479ce0e25de292dd48c5c796364

subject: Resolve parameter list including nested stacks
messages:
[{'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:11:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:13:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Workflow-1

Still a WIP, posting to get some eyes on it since I'm pretty new to Heat development.

The biggest thing that is missing is adding a recursive layer to address stacks that nest multiple times. Currently, this will work with an example using a parent template and any number of nested stacks at that level."}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:16:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sample output:

heat template-validate -f parent.yaml -e env.yaml 
{
  "NestedParameters": {
    "nested-resource-1": {
      "nested-1-p2": {
        "Default": "", 
        "Type": "String", 
        "NoEcho": "false", 
        "Description": "not set by parent, should be considered a param_default parameter", 
        "Label": "nested-1-p2"
      }
    }, 
    "nested-resource-2": {
      "nested-2-p2": {
        "Default": "", 
        "Type": "String", 
        "NoEcho": "false", 
        "Description": "not set by parent, should be considered a param_default parameter", 
        "Label": "nested-2-p2"
      }
    }
  }, 
  "Description": "parent template", 
  "Parameters": {
    "parent-p1": {
      "Default": "foo", 
      "Type": "String", 
      "NoEcho": "false", 
      "Description": "parent first parameter", 
      "Label": "parent-p1"
    }
  }
}

Of note in there is that each nested template also includes a nested-*-p1 parameter. The value for it is set by the parent template when the resource is created, therefore it is not included in the returned result here. Once I get the recursion in place I can add a flag that will control this behavior v. including all nested parameters.'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:42:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-08-31 20:42:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-08-31 21:30:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I haven't re-run the unit tests locally since the last patchset, but that's mostly because I'm just submitting this to get an opinion on the approach."}, {'account_id': 8399, 'date': '2015-09-02 21:19:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

Looking for some advice here.

After some investigation, the validate templates call is always using URL fetch to retrieve templates from the resource_registry. This worked fine for me when testing templates from the same box, but is obviously an incorrect approach. Instead, the files dict passed into the REST call should be propagated into the validate call and used to retrieve the template contents if possible before falling back to URL fetch similar to what template_data() does in TemplateResourceInfo (which I can't use and will describe why later).

The code that does that was added back on 3/14/14 in commit 4585f1e alongside the ability to dynamically create a new class for each nested template (which I'm not fully sure I understand the purpose of).

I see why it calls the urlfetch stuff directly. There is a bit of a chicken and the egg problem. The chain goes from engine -> Environment -> ResourceRegistry -> TemplateResourceInfo when calling to dynamically create a new class for a nested template, doesn't have access to the template contents. That's why they are loaded in that generate_class method. The files dictionary, however, is stored in a Template object and not in the chain I described above. Without the Template object, we don't have a handle on the files, but without the files, we can't create the Template object needed for the class generation. And I can't use template_data in TemplateResourceInfo since I don't have an instance of that class since this code is creating a new subclass of it.

After a few approaches, I finally decided to simply propagate the files dict through the chain I described above to see if it would work. It did work, but I don't like it as a solution. It's ugly in the sense that the files dict was never in this chain to begin with because it really didn't need to be. It also resulted in an instanceof check in ResourceRegistry since the only *ResourceInfo class that cares about the files is the TemplateResourceInfo.

The problem is, I can't figure out another way of doing it. One option is to utilize the same mechanism that stack create does, but that goes through a Stack object which also feels unnatural in this case since we don't actually have a stack when simply validating a template.

So I'm posting this for advice. Is the approach of propagating files acceptable to everyone? Is there another option I'm missing short of rewriting a massive amount of the validation logic (which, as per a previous comment, I'd still like to do in the future to decouple it from the engine)?

Thanks  :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-09-02 23:06:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

commit_message:
Resolve parameter list including nested stacks

Changes the validate template call to also include a dict of parameters
from any nested stacks found. The parameters included are only those
that are not passed into the stack during the resource's creation (in
other words, the parameters intended to be set via parameter_defaults).

Implements-blueprint: nested-validation
Change-Id: Idb51c983fc07e49d371b8ccb3cea6f7e92f99903

commit_message:
Put horizon in its own process

This change makes mod_wsgi create standalone processes for horizon. This
avoids obscure start up errors when mod_wsgi needs to spawn a new
process or thread. These restarts occur, for example, when mod_wsgi
receives a request from a client that is accessing the service through a
non-standard SSL port that is mapped to the port mod_wsgi is listening
on.

Change-Id: I5907b5c06cef0272ee145c277f79f23ba37741a4
Closes-Bug: #1499073
(cherry picked from commit f28e412db72845a4623318d5aacc50fddc0cb8ea)

lxc_net_netmask: 255.255.255.0
lxc_net_dhcp_range: 10.255.255.2,10.255.255.253

lxc_net_address value which will not overlap with an IP already
assigned to the host.

(cherry picked from commit 238c06baa89fe62bc0d70166cb08234ff33623e4)
"}]
commit_message:
Do not use default LXC network in gate

hpcloud-b4's eth0 uses 10.0.3.0/24, which overlaps with the
lxc_net_address default.  This commit sets the following in the gate:

lxc_net_address: 10.255.255.1
lxc_net_netmask: 255.255.255.0
lxc_net_dhcp_range: 10.255.255.2,10.255.255.253

At some point we'll need to implement a mechanism to determine valid
lxc_net_address value which will not overlap with an IP already
assigned to the host.

Change-Id: Ib4df050be2d8734c636b6adcc81a53258796b5a8
(cherry picked from commit 238c06baa89fe62bc0d70166cb08234ff33623e4)

commit_message:
Implement auth_endpoint_type parameter

Add auth_endpoint_type which is the type of endpoint in Identity service
catalog to use for communication with OpenStack services. Default to
undef.

Change-Id: Ia62186b3a4520e1f323a4fa96d8a925874b3604a

Replace '' by undef for auth_tenant_id paramater.
Using undef follow Puppet best practice.

commit_message:
rspec: run tests for ::ceilometer::agent::auth

This patch actually run rpsec test for ::ceilometer::agent::auth
class, and also drop an invalid parameter to make test working.

The class was introduced by [1] but test never ran before.
[1] I167c6c570bdebb4be2ef99cd0b9cf81f37856d9f

Change-Id: Ifcdd2d149e8b15446087ddc258d54d87dea1e8c0

commit_message:
compute agent: do not try to configure nova.conf

Back in history, we tried to configure something in nova.conf which is
now managed by puppet-nova. It causes the module conflicting with
puppet-nova and makes Puppet runs not idempotent and nova.conf with
wrong parameters.

nova_notifier plugin was removed in Kilo (ceilometer commit eed463659f2e6f7018b5db1fcae9931ae1d60a00).

Change-Id: I2b8d55613f0a962662d67b9fd82db17b758af80f

Update rpc_backend default parameter

rpc_backend should be 'rabbit' which is the default in Olso Messaging.
This patch update the default and the conditional.

Change-Id: I392dc5670d8b9ebb8c58e06c8cadd44a4adb1694

commit_message:
Cleanup configure_delegated_roles deprecated parameter

In Kilo, we decided to use ::heat::keystone::auth to manage the
Keystone_role resource to help with Trusts configuration.
Though the configuration was and still remains part of ::heat::engine
class because we assume ::heat::keystone::auth can be run outside the
heat-engine node.

So this patch aims to drop the deprecated parameter, update the
documentation and unit tests.

Change-Id: I045a3a82095e23778c4e878b13f2fc7f561d680e

Feedback welcome re breaking the historical compatibility between native/AWS policy and ASG resources.'}, {'account_id': 12606, 'date': '2015-03-04 17:32:22.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

A better structure for autoscaling groups would be with a base class that has the common behavior (like the adjust() method). Then aws and native can inherit.

I think what I propose inline should be done first, as restructuring these resources is a much larger job.

I would include the ResourceGroup in the discussions about restructuring autoscaling groups, maybe that can be the base class that can have the adjust() method that is used for aws and native autoscaling.'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2015-03-04 21:38:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)

> I think what I propose inline should be done first, as restructuring these resources is a much larger job.

Qiming is already working on it, and it is indeed a much larger job.  

Inheriting from ResourceGroup has it's own problems because the two group resources have diverged to have some incompatible interfaces and characteristics (e.g nested resource names as indexes vs random names).  

In the end, having seen what the inheritance model looked like for group resources (some initial patches were posted), I think we decided that a flat model where AWS and native resources are fully decoupled is better, with a library of utility functions shared between the two.

Anyway, somewhat OT for this review, but thanks for the feedback :)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2015-03-05 00:11:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

Well, the motivation behind this change is to enable exposing more flexible adjustment interfaces to operators, such as in future sending a signal to remove a specific member from the group.

So, yes, adding additional operations in future commits does make sense, but I'm not sure about those you mention:

- resize_desired is already covered by either the exact_capacity signal, or the desired_capacity property on create/update.

- min/max values are already specified via properties, so I'm not sure what re-specifying them via a signal would mean'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2015-04-09 09:20:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

[{'created': '2014-12-22 16:55:31.000000000', 'message': "Convert AutoScalingGroup adjustments to handle_signal

Currently, we use a non-standard adjust() interface to couple the
ScalingPolicy and AutoScalingGroup resources.  It's better if we
move towards a consistent model where all asychronous inter-resource
signalling uses the standard handle_signal plugin API, for the following
reasons:
- Better scalability and better for convergence architecture due to less
  coupled resources (because the signal can be sent via RPC in future).
- Better for debuggability and operators, because ASG adjustments can
  be triggered via heat resource-signal
- We can more easily allow the native and AWS-compatible implementations
  to diverge, when we only use standard plugin interfaces.

Note at the moment we don't make the ASG resources SignalResponder's,
and we don't expose a URL for them.  This is because Ceilometer currently
gives us no control over the alarm post body, so we need an intermdiate
ScalingPolicy resource to enable adjustment context to be added to the
signal.  This doesn't preclude developer/operator signalling via heat
resource-signal, it's just means you can't directly define signal
relationships triggering the ASG adjustment inside the templates yet.

Change-Id: I7c5cd627277906509fb794a3090625e9b459a760

commit_message:
Convert AutoScalingGroup adjustments to handle_signal

Currently, we use a non-standard adjust() interface to couple the
ScalingPolicy and AutoScalingGroup resources.  It's better if we
move towards a consistent model where all asychronous inter-resource
signalling uses the standard handle_signal plugin API, for the following
reasons:
- Better scalability and better for convergence architecture due to less
  coupled resources (because the signal can be sent via RPC in future).
- Better for debuggability and operators, because ASG adjustments can
  be triggered via heat resource-signal
- We can more easily allow the native and AWS-compatible implementations
  to diverge, when we only use standard plugin interfaces.
- Easier interfacing with non-policy actors for triggering ASG adjustments
  for example, having mistral drive scaling adjustments via workflow.

Note at the moment we don't make the ASG resources SignalResponder's,
and we don't expose a URL for them.  This is because Ceilometer currently
gives us no control over the alarm post body, so we need an intermdiate
ScalingPolicy resource to enable adjustment context to be added to the
signal.  This doesn't preclude developer/operator (or even mistral) signalling
via heat resource-signal, it's just means you can't directly define signal
relationships triggering the ASG adjustment inside the templates yet.

Change-Id: I7c5cd627277906509fb794a3090625e9b459a760

commit_message:
Disable max_resources_per_stack by default

In my testing I've found this to have a completely unacceptable overhead
whenever you use non-trivial amounts of nesting, e.g a ResourceGroup
containing a nested stack with one RandomString resource takes 500%
more time just due to this check with large counts for the ResoureGroup.

Unless we can make this *much* less expensive, I think we should find
other ways to prevent users DoSing the service with very large stacks
which don't damage performance this much.

Change-Id: I0f08d410eb86154b3373a94f5cbdf5a53635a509
Closes-Bug: #1489548

I don't personally think this is something that should be installed via os-ansible-deployment.  It may be a security best practice there may be performance implications running this so I'd rather leave it to the deployer to decide if it should be installed or not."}, {'account_id': 538, 'date': '2015-09-14 14:31:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

What are the performance concerns?

If we're worried about disk space utilization, we can add a configuration to limit audit logs to a certain size.

CPU load and disk usage from auditd is fairly low and much lower than rsyslog."}, {'account_id': 7307, 'date': '2015-09-15 08:27:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I have no specific concerns, as I don't use auditd.  However, a google search for 'auditd performance' brings up a number of applicable results.

In the past we pushed back on including software like this (software which isn't a hard requirement to install/operate openstack-ansible), and this is primarily why I've -1 this review.  However, if others feel that every openstack-ansible install would benefit from having auditd installed and we are sure this isn't going to introduce any blanket performance issues, then I will happily remove my non-blocking -1."}, {'account_id': 6816, 'date': '2015-09-15 08:48:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

While I think that there may be value installing this onto hosts, I don't think that simply installing it adds any value. I would prefer to see this be added as an optional item, defaulted to not installing, along with some documentation describing why one would install it and with reference to docs describing how to use it."}, {'account_id': 7219, 'date': '2015-09-15 10:34:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I agree with the other opinions expressed that including non-essential packages, while potentially useful, should not be something forced on a deployment. I don't believe there has been a great deal of discussion on how these optional elements should be managed or included so it would be good to have a more detailed review of this element of the project."}, {'account_id': 538, 'date': '2015-09-17 13:24:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 7219, 'date': '2015-09-17 14:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Install auditd on the host

Running auditd on the host is a generally recommended security best practice
and it allows an administrator to see details AppArmor denials much easier.
This can help with general troubleshooting and security investigations.

Closes-Bug: 1491915

Change-Id: Ib657f3c3093765e6ca45a9e1fd74d7c23891df3d

commit_message:
shell: improve error info

On error, this changes the output from:

 Bad Request (HTTP 400)
 <a bunch of html>

to:

  Bad Request (HTTP 400)
  <the actual source of error>

Which looks wayyyy better.

Change-Id: I1a96b2ceecb45db668dd3246fce4453ee2a6b1d0

commit_message:
Remove pypy jobs from the requirements repository

The pypy jobs have been failing for a while and are non-voting. Let's
stop running them for now, and restore them when/if we find someone to
pick up the pypy work again.

Change-Id: I3996a8c61b029e3b1c2a4b14f95fdf6483f27209

Only fix volume generators if upgrade target environment was deployed by Fuel
5.2.9 (5.1.1 variant). Other supported releases don't need this fix.

Rob"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2015-09-24 17:00:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Since the code was previously open sourced and had apache2 license, adding a proprietary license to the lib now does seem to be a regression.  Usually it is the other way around - moving from proprietary to open source.'}, {'account_id': 15100, 'date': '2015-09-25 01:45:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

run huawei-ci'}, {'account_id': 7102, 'date': '2015-09-25 06:50:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@Robert: The problem is not that you split the code and use netapp_lib now. That's fine and also useful because you can use the same code for Cinder and Manila.
The problem is the license of netapp_lib. As a distribution (or a deployer), I can't just take the library from pypi and package it and redistribute it (i.e. with SUSE OpenStack Cloud, Ubuntu, Mirantis, RDO, ...). So this is a regression because using NetApp as a Cinder/Manila backend was working out of the box before the switch to netapp_lib when using one of the OpenStack distributors.
I saw in #openstack-cinder that you said others are doing the same and your example was hp3parclient . The difference between netapp_lib and hp3parclient is the license. hp3parclient is released under Apache-2.0. So everybody can just redistribute hp3parclient."}, {'account_id': 2417, 'date': '2015-09-25 12:03:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Thomas: NetApp heard your concern and has decided to agree with you and remove netapp-lib from both Manila and Cinder. However I think that NetApp prefers to remove it themselves (to make sure that the revert doesn't break anything) so expect to see another patch within the next 4 hours or so. If you're okay with that +1 the other patch and abandon this one."}, {'account_id': 7102, 'date': '2015-09-25 12:42:37.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

NetApp will provide another patch to solve the license issue.'}]

commit_message:
Cached file should not be deleted if time equal to master

The cached file was being deleted when the modification times were
identical. This causes an issue especially with local storage of the
master images as a hard link is done and the cache file would always be
flagged as out of date.

Also give more details when the cached file is deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1499601
Change-Id: I0964c84028271b8a11e1178463bb2d513ce26410

Sure. My reasoning is: the situation when neutron quotas are disabled (according to get_disabled_quotas()) can be caused either by neutron itself being disabled, by neutron quotas extension being disabled or by disabling the corresponding setting in horizon config - or by any combination of these 3 factors that makes sense. Well, in case we're dealing with neutron-specific buttons, we're interested in 2 latter factors. The good thing with get_disabled_quotas() is that it doesn't matter why quotas are disabled - it catches all the cases when it doesn't make sense to set them - so why should we distinguish them?"}, {'account_id': 4264, 'date': '2015-08-27 11:39:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Neutron Quota Settings Flag Disables Neutron GUI

if OPENSTACK_NEUTRON_NETWORK["enable_quotas"] = False buttons will not appear
and exceptions are thrown.   This is because a dict is searched for a key
("available") which wont be there if its disabled.  This generates a
KeyError at runtime.

As currently written enable_quatas -> False essentially disables Neutron usage.
This is not a desirable outcome.

This patch shows Neutron related buttons and ignores the quota settings,
which seems more in line with the notion of disabling quotas.

Closes-Bug:#1482354
Change-Id: I9485ddeece74d87317c2587498f5f79d4ffdb66e

This patch adds functional test for lb_policy. Since all lbaas
driver interfaces are faked in this patch, integration test is
needed for more complete verification.

commit_message:
Optimize cluster action construction

This patch moves the loading logic into the cluster action constructor.
A closer examination revealed that there is no risk that the target
cluster cannot be found (including direct action construction and those
triggered from webhook). Even there are such cases, we can leave it as a
future todo.

The intent of this change is to make cluster an attribute of the action
so that we don't have to pass it around.

Change-Id: Ic3cffa7a7f6a3b541afb2c5700aadf270bfa5c10

commit_message:
Also use EPEL mirror for overcloud image builds

We have seen improvements by using the EPEL mirror while
building the undercloud but we are still seeing occasional
failures on overcloud image builds, we should use a mirror
there also.

Change-Id: I9aa5be56133c643858f8d223bd36e3b621c1ef32

commit_message:
Bump minimum version of oslo.i18n

This reflects the minimum required version of oslo.i18n as required by
oslo.utils>=1.4.0:

    http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/oslo.utils/tree/requirements.txt?id=1.4.0

Change-Id: Ic5ca0232bbc341afd89f07f484d4b5f1a78e4b89
Closes-Bug: 1492951

commit_message:
Don't use python with run_process

First noted in change id by fumihiko and kyle:
I079e18b58b214bf8362945c253d6d894ca8b1a6b

Neutron and few others seem to use an extra "python" along
with run_process which is quite unnecessary and complicates
adding python3 support in devstack. So let's clean this up.

Change-Id: I2d478f2b04c04d05c18420563e2ad77eba73be3f

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. Also it
    takes generally at least a couple of weeks for cores to get around to
    reviewing code. The more you participate in the community the more
    rewarding it is for you. You may also notice that the more you get to know
    people and get to be known, the faster your patches will be reviewed and
    eventually approved. Get to know others and become known by doing code
    reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

commit_message:
Ceph Ansible support

Add the initial playbooks for making ceph and ansible play nice
together.

This does not include all of the openstack changes to make things like
nova, glance, and cinder work. This will simply build the ceph cluster
and thats it. The next patchset will do the OpenStack integration.

DocImpact
Change-Id: Ie1697dde5f92e833652933a80f0004f31b641330
Partially-Implements: blueprint ceph-container

commit_message:
Request logs on failure

It's common to run Nova logging at DEBUG, because if you run at
anything higher, when a failure occurs you won't have enough
information to diagnose the failure. What we really want is to run at
at INFO usually and log at DEBUG only for those requests which fail.
This spec describes a way to achieve this without inducing temporal
paradox.

Change-Id: Iccadb7eb81532d58a3246b50938c6d1007eab584

commit_message:
Do not use default LXC network in gate

hpcloud-b4's eth0 uses 10.0.3.0/24, which overlaps with the
lxc_net_address default.  This commit sets the following in the gate:

lxc_net_address: 10.255.255.1
lxc_net_netmask: 255.255.255.0
lxc_net_dhcp_range: 10.255.255.2,10.255.255.253

At some point we'll need to implement a mechanism to determine valid
lxc_net_address value which will not overlap with an IP already
assigned to the host.

Change-Id: Ib4df050be2d8734c636b6adcc81a53258796b5a8

commit_message:
Change Manilaclient to use --os-region-name param

Manilaclient ignores --os-region-param now. Change client from
'manilaclient/v1/client.py' to use first endpoint with a matching region.

Closes-bug: #1450613

Change-Id: I7fd76b0d874a91952513c40b4a7bdb0c45241dad
(cherry picked from commit 0d257aedce8305f6742bdc49548491578d515965)

commit_message:
replace the hard-coded history list with an auto-generated one

Replace the hand curated list of changes with the one generated by pbr
automatically.

At the same time, change the toctree settings in index.rst to avoid
showing every release of stevedore at the top level and to clean up the
amount of nesting showing for other entries.

Change-Id: I3fb9306c0ca3ce6ed9681ffeaa8b9b8ed0f2bd7c

commit_message:
Neutronclient: Move functional tests to check queue

Since the jobs are now working in experimental queue, moving them
to the check queue as non-voting. Once it has had some test time,
will make jobs voting and remove gate-neutronclient-dsvm-functional.

gate-neutronclient-test-dsvm-functional
gate-neutronclient-test-dsvm-functional-adv-svcs

Change-Id: I8aca48cc7eb2bab2a554abdb880a66f761109cee
Partial-Bug: 1484148

commit_message:
Renaming state DELAYED to RUNNING_DELAYED

* As discussed in the mailing list it's better to rename DELAYED
  to RUNNING_DELAYED so that we semantically express it as a substate
  of RUNNING whereas WAITING is not.

Closes-Bug: #1470369
Change-Id: I3b7033d894d29fe755d4d0262c1029c4576421cd

commit_message:
Name the package `gnocchiclient'

There is no good reason to name this python-gnocchiclient, except
following the bad trend started with OpenStack. Let's be smarter and use
gnocchiclient on PyPI.

Change-Id: I05957ae04223ceb7c89b46f7548bf88570971a13

The thing is that when using 'yum install package1 package2'
yum is not going to fail if one of the packages fails to
install. Instead we use 'echo package1 package2 | xargs -n1 yum install'
to install them in turn.

Change-Id: I878d6c2589636aa39495c0fefc0c1dc9f1b33a56
Closes-Bug: #1465388

commit_message:
Install rpm packages one by one using xargs and yum

The thing is that when using 'yum install package1 package2'
yum is not going to fail if one of the packages fails to
install. Instead we use 'echo package1 package2 | xargs -n1 yum install'
to install them in turn.

Change-Id: I878d6c2589636aa39495c0fefc0c1dc9f1b33a56
Closes-Bug: #1465388

This patch moves re/un/install commands for Tempest from "tempest"
category to "verify" category. Now to re/un/install Tempest we can
execute the following commands:

    $ rally verify install
    $ rally verify uninstall
    $ rally verify reinstall

In addition, missing unit tests were added.

commit_message:
Moving commands for (re,un)instaling Tempest to "verify" category

This patch moves (re,un)install commands for Tempest from "tempest"
category to "verify" category. Now to (re,un)install Tempest we can
execute the following commands:

    $ rally verify install
    $ rally verify uninstall
    $ rally verify reinstall

In addition, missing unit tests were added. The corresponding changes
were made in rally-verify.sh script to pass Jenkins check.

Implements: blueprint improve-tempest-manage-cli

Change-Id: Ibe6713b755982acf1f7e4b89b13fd2a0dad7c034

commit_message:
Test for multiple networks with templates

This test is targeting to cover feature
node groups when there is a need for
further improvement in flexibility
via applying network template.

Related blueprint templates-for-networking
Closes-bug: #1479743

Change-Id: I315db40005c7fe21baa283e4b22c706ce5226838

commit_message:
Remove dummy/placeholder 'ChangeLog' as its not needed

Just enforce that `python setup.py build_sphinx` will be the
way to build docs (which also builds a 'ChangeLog') so we don't
need to maintain a dummy file here anymore.

Change-Id: Icec9173c7970d84c105f151ac74dc9080ab3b1f7

commit_message:
Create nova-bug-report cmd utility

This got shortly discussed during the Liberty Midcycle event.
The contributors need certain information from a bug report to do a
proper bug triage and/or to have criteria if patches for this bug
really solve the described issue. To provide this information in each
bug report, the reporter has to collect them manually, although
OpenStack is already aware of most of the information. The collecting
of the information is cumbersome and sometimes the reporter doesn't
exactly know what is needed, so it is often omitted in the reports.
The turnaround time of bugs could be decreased if the reporter has a
means to collect the debug information automatically.
The artifact of an execution of this means should then contain enough
information to attach it to a bug report.

Implements: blueprint nova-bug-report

Change-Id: I8df9feff106598226900173f8d12863567cdd73f

commit_message:
Configure HAProxy SSL frontends with cipher suite

For increased security against possible SSL attacks, configure HAProxy
SSL frontends with a cipher suite. Default to the existing
ssl_cipher_suite variable defined in user_variables.

Change-Id: Ida64765bb4ebec0bbfa118e2eeedfb36ad2bd3f8
Closes-Bug: #1498726

commit_message:
Fix separate keystone add node test

- Memcache is running on keystone and controller nodes
so hiera memcache_roles output is different for these
nodes and we need to check them separately

Change-Id: I23735d6f1dff391606b11bae91113a5c3b505fee
Closes-Bug: #1496039
(cherry picked from commit 8e4de22fec7c8c60b94664ec080b21260bb212c0)

commit_message:
Use tempest-lib's token_client

Now tempest-lib provides token_client modules as library and the
interface is stable. So neutron repogitory doesn't need to contain
these modules.
This patch makes neutron use tempest-lib's token_client and removes
the own modules for the maintenance.

Change-Id: Ieff7eb003f6e8257d83368dbc80e332aa66a156c

Use PRODUCTION from astute.yaml when build_images=1 mode is active

This patch is a part of version.yaml deprecation plan.

commit_message:
Fix separate keystone add node test

- Memcache is running on keystone and controller nodes
so hiera memcache_roles output is different for these
nodes and we need to check them separately

Change-Id: I23735d6f1dff391606b11bae91113a5c3b505fee
Closes-Bug: #1496039

commit_message:
Workflow definition updated, when workbook is created

While creating workbook, workflow definition was not saved to
database. Due to which user was unable to see workflow definition

Change-Id: I0e3518be17198eadcc57a2eb8f15dc25266d338a
Closes-Bug: #1493343

commit_message:
[Ref Arch] OVS endpoints configuration using FUEL CLI

-The YAML example was modified to show all available options.
-To use ovs bridging for endpoints "provider: ovs" added
 for each endpoint name in transformation part.
-YAML examples moved to the corresponding folder

Change-Id: I5b0641cc084d0c3ff37860793c27e772aed19dca
Closes-Bug: 1365080
Closes-Bug: 1455534

commit_message:
Using six.iteritems() to avoid some python3 tests failure

Fixed the following failure:
AttributeError: 'dict' object has no attribute 'iteritems'

This patch belongs to improvement of python3 compatibility in Mistral.

Partial-Bug: #1378537

commit_message:
Neutronclient: one command for all associations

With this change, the association cli becomes:

neutron bgpvpn-associate <bgpvpn-uui> --network <net-uuid>

(this change also adds 'networks' in the list of
fields shown by the bgpvpn-list command, which is
very useful)

Change-Id: If5ff5a43815b29a983199047e85211bc0f4e3136
Closes-Bug: 1496905

commit_message:
Fixing std.create_instance workflow

 * Now it is possible to pass network info, keypair name
   and security groups info to std.create_instance
 * ssh_username and ssh_password arguments are optional.

Closes-Bug: #1404204

Change-Id: I08e06a2f1239433f00fac4288486177d6c64ffcd

commit_message:
CLI : remove the '--network' argument for (dis)associate

We choose to mimic the behavior or the 'router-interface-add'
for network association/disassociation to bgpvpns. We should
also mimic the CLI usage.
With this fix, the user won't have to add the '--network' when
running bgpvpn-network-(dis)associate commands.
This patch also rename methods that should have been renamed during
Ia624c54a513c6c36183a196601d29993fcf7e023

Change-Id: Ic112548e64ca5799cd5e4887a7c070b973b62cd4

commit_message:
Add non-voting gate-designate-python34 check job

The designate is being ported to Python 3 by Pradeep Kumar Singh.  A
non-voting check job will help to validate the work on Python 3 until
the check is fixed. For example, the change
Id55343dad75d692ed3df15d16211fcce4ef6aaf2 should fix the python34
check job.

Exclude stable branches (Juno, Kilo), only Liberty is being ported to
Python 3.

Partially-Implements: blueprint designate-py3
Change-Id: I853798bd72b1982a538ededfb8c5472173a6f79a

Update GCE API jobs

We are working on resuscitation of GCE API project

commit_message:
Cleanup of Translations

In preparation for the release, do some cleanups for translations.

Removes all po files that are partially translated. The translation
team has decided to exclude files with less than 66 % of translated
content. There is no content lost, all data is in the translation
server, we just remove it from the repository.

This updates also recreates all pot (translation source files) to
reflect the state of the repository.

This change needs to be done manually since the automatic import does
not handle some of these cases.

Depends-On: Icf355f9a6d667371a4f2b6077ca4954e1351e92d
Change-Id: I6f6662af780a002ed37c79bdd8fdd12fac110d4b

commit_message:
Created a dockerfile that runs Anchor

It works but probably doesn't run Anchor in the best way.

Once this is in the repo I can create a docker build job that
will auto generate a new upstream anchor image each time a new
merge occurs. When that is established, the process for running
the container can be simplified.

Change-Id: Ida199d4286a4b476e52d69864c97ff24633ca073

revisions:
[{'created': '2015-09-24 00:54:09.000000000', 'message': "Remove green worker reference to its executor

There really is no need to give a green worker
a reference to its creator and it hinders/makes it
harder for python to garbage collect the executor
and its workers.

It is also not used, so let's make the python
garbage collectors life easier by not even passing
it in.

Change-Id: I0f9d27663c3ca5ca908ef6f90f3d1d0f6b5f9104
"}]
commit_message:
Remove green worker reference to its executor

There really is no need to give a green worker
a reference to its creator and it hinders/makes it
harder for python to garbage collect the executor
and its workers.

It is also not used, so let's make the python
garbage collectors life easier by not even passing
it in.

Change-Id: I0f9d27663c3ca5ca908ef6f90f3d1d0f6b5f9104

commit_message:
Check if version is read-only when querying Zanata

Extend query-zanata-project-version.py to parse the response it gets
back from the Zanata server, and to also exit 1 if the version is marked
as read-only, saves the proposal slave performing the work if the server
will reject the upload anyway.

Change-Id: I9f66bd34c6d34703b47836f91737282193beb0af

This commit adds a new error message to the InvalidCredentials
exception raised when creating a new credentials object. Previously
it would just fail saying invalid credentials which wasn't
particularly useful for debugging what about the fields passed in was
invalid. The new error message will inform the user which key was the
cause of the error.

Change-Id: I49941321db7d6259080d706b687ac27173a3bffe
"}]
commit_message:
Add exception message to invalid cred field

This commit adds a new error message to the InvalidCredentials
exception raised when creating a new credentials object. Previously
it would just fail saying invalid credentials which wasn't
particularly useful for debugging what about the fields passed in was
invalid. The new error message will inform the user which key was the
cause of the error.

Change-Id: I49941321db7d6259080d706b687ac27173a3bffe
